%[text] # R07: Metabolomics — Analysis of Plasma Biomarkers for Type 2 Diabetes
%[text] EasyMolKit Research — Layer 4
%[text] Modern mass spectrometry can measure dozens of metabolites from a single blood sample, but interpreting those values requires multiple analytical perspectives.
%[text] Large cohort studies (Wang 2011, Newgard 2009) show that in Type 2 Diabetes (T2D), branched-chain amino acids (BCAA: Ile/Leu/Val) and carbohydrates increase while TCA cycle intermediates decrease.
%[text] "What is the structure of that metabolite?" "Which pathway is disrupted?" "Can we model the abnormal glucose dynamics?" Few environments support all three questions in a single workflow.
%[text] This script explores T2D metabolic abnormalities across four layers (structure, statistics, pathway, and dynamics), focusing on 30 plasma metabolites.
%[text] 
%[text] ### Learning Objectives
%[text] - Understand the data analysis flow of untargeted metabolomics (descriptor calculation → t-test → BH multiple testing correction → volcano plot).
%[text] - Discover metabolite groups that covary chemically using Morgan fingerprints and hierarchical clustering (Application A02).
%[text] - Understand the principles of pathway enrichment analysis using hypergeometric distribution tests.
%[text] - Retrieve pathway information by calling the KEGG REST API via biopython (optional).
%[text] - Construct a feedback ODE model of glucose-insulin-hepatic glucose production using SimBiology or ode45, and visualize the T2D pathology numerically.
%[text] - Utilize the output of `emk.descriptor.batchCalculate()` for statistical analysis and visualization. \
%[text] 
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of A02 (Molecular Clustering) — Concept of hierarchical clustering
%[text] - Completion of R02 (PK/PD Simulation) — Basics of ODE modeling
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (ttest2, linkage, dendrogram, hygecdf)
%[text] - Bioinformatics Toolbox (enhanced pathway annotation. Fallback to built-in data if unavailable)
%[text] - SimBiology Toolbox (ODE modeling. Fallback to ode45 for equivalent results if unavailable)
%[text] - biopython (KEGG REST API access. Optional): `emk.setup.installExtra("biopython")` \
%[text] 
%[text] ### Operating Environment
%[text] Operates on both Desktop (Windows) and MATLAB Online (Campus / Free).
%[text] - Without Statistics Toolbox → Some parts of Sections 2-4 fallback to manual implementation
%[text] - Without Bioinformatics → Use built-in KEGG mapping table
%[text] - Without SimBiology → Fallback to ode45 (results are equivalent)
%[text] - Without biopython → Skip KEGG REST access
%[text] - Required time: 45-90 minutes \
%[text] 
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Wang TJ et al. (2011) Metabolite profiles and the risk of developing diabetes. Nat Med 17:448-453. \[BCAA as T2D risk biomarkers\]
%[text] - Newgard CB et al. (2009) A branched-chain amino acid-related metabolic signature. Cell Metab 9:311-326. \[BCAA and insulin resistance\]
%[text] - Karlsson FH et al. (2013) Gut metagenome in European women with normal, impaired and diabetic glucose control. Nature 498:99-103. \[Gut microbiota metabolites and T2D\]
%[text] - Dalla Man C et al. (2007) Meal simulation model of the glucose-insulin system. IEEE Trans Biomed Eng 54:1740-1749. \[Section 5 ODE model foundation\]
%[text] - Cock PJA et al. (2009) Biopython: freely available Python tools. Bioinformatics 25:1422-1423. \[Section 4 biopython KEGG REST API\]
%[text] - Willett P et al. (1998) Chemical similarity searching. J Chem Inf Comput Sci 38:983-996. \[Section 3 Tanimoto similarity clustering\] \
%[text] 
%[text] RUN: Execute each section with Ctrl+Enter
%%
